{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":222,"record_hash":"sha256:2d3e9759d0d66ed768be62359bae25dddea2d91d90ecfdda27e4edf771af2cad","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:32:05.610Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 193667\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1486\nOutput:\nteam, explicit-share, and richer publication flows are later work.\n\n## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n\nFor public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\non demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\nURL.\n\nThis only works when `refs/meta/main` has actually been published to the public\nGitHub repository. Forge's existing `but-sync` flow pushes metadata to private\ncode.storage workspace refs such as `refs/<client_id>/meta/*`; that does not\nmake metadata available to URL-replacement reviewers. Agent Trail v1 assumes\npublic metadata already exists and should show a missing-metadata state when it\ndoes not. Publishing metadata to GitHub can be a later GitButler/GitMeta\ndistribution feature.\n\nExample local setup:\n\n```ini\n[remote \"meta\"]\n  url = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n  fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n  meta = true\n  promisor = true\n  partialclonefilter = blob:none\n```\n\nThe server should not assume it can see a developer's local Git remote config.\nGiven a URL like:\n\n```text\nhttps://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nthe server should resolve the public GitHub repository, then fetch\n`refs/meta/main` from that same public repository.\n\nPossible first flow:\n\n1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n2. fetch GitHub PR metadata through public-equivalent access and verify that the\n   repository and pull request are public/readable\n3. reject fork pull requests for v1\n4. create or refresh a server-side scratch/cache repository for the repository\n5. fetch `refs/meta/main`\n6. resolve the fetched metadata ref to an OID\n7. run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n   the fetched repository metadata\n8. generate an Agent Trail snapshot from the `but-agentlog` public/read\n   projection\n9. cache or return that snapshot according to the retention policy\n\nThe server can lazy-initialize repository st\n[TRUNCATED]\nrequest.\n\n## Relationship Model\n\nOne pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\npull requests or branches.\n\nThe durable object remains the project-scoped session. Pull requests, reviews,\nand branches should reference session or turn keys; they should not own copies\nof transcript records. Change targets remain available in `but-agentlog`, but\nAgent Trail v1 does not query them.\n\n## Review Experience\n\nThe default view should be compact and review-focused.\n\nShow:\n\n- what the human asked the agent to do\n- what the agent said it changed\n- what commands or tools it ran\n- what validation passed or failed\n  handle\n- snapshot identity is derived from repository identity, PR facts/version,\n  metadata ref OID, projection version, and selected evidence digest\n- stable PR route revalidates metadata before display; unchanged metadata OID,\n  projection version, and selected keys may reuse a snapshot; changed inputs\n  generate a new internal snapshot id\n- fork PRs are unsupported\n- Forge does not implement an extra public redaction layer\n- Forge should not shell out to `but agentlog`; add a public `but-agentlog`\n  library API or smaller read/projection crate before public rendering\n\n## Ready For Build\n\nThe product direction is clear enough to start, but the UI is blocked on the\ndata contract. The first build should start with the load-bearing API boundary:\n\n1. add the `but-agentlog` public/read projection API or split a smaller\n   read/projection crate\n2. make that API accept PR facts and return allowlisted Agent Trail projection\n   data\n3. prove the redaction, bounds, match reasons, and drill-down handles with\n   fixtures\n4. add a Forge Rust projection helper binary that wraps the API and speaks JSON\n5. build the Forge TypeScript API route, GitHub lookup, metadata fetch/cache\n   path, and snapshot generation against that helper\n6. build the page UI against the API route\n\nDo not start by rendering raw `but-agentlog` CLI output in Forge. That would\nskip the main safety boundary in this design.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:32:05.610Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}